    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a heavy emphasis on high-ceiling power-speed combinations, headlined by **Yordan Alvarez** (74.41) and **Trea Turner** (70.46). **Yordan Alvarez** faces a favorable matchup against Cecconi, where his elite xwOBA of 0.393 and top-of-the-order placement maximize his scoring potential. Similarly, **Trea Turner** remains our primary engine for stolen bases; despite a modest -4% adjustment for the opposing catcher\u2019s efficiency, his dynamic ability to capitalize on Rea\u2019s 4.36 xERA makes him our most dangerous weapon on the basepaths. **Kyle Schwarber** (69.69) rounds out our top-tier trio, benefiting from a +8% order premium as he looks to leverage his 0.402 xwOBA against a vulnerable pitching staff.\n\nOur most intriguing roster decision today centers on the outfield and the bottom of the order. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (60.49) earns a start despite a lower-tier batting order position because his dynamic platoon advantage (+14%) outweighs the risks posed by a tough catcher. Conversely, **Dillon Dingler** (36.10) sits on the bench as our most difficult omission; while he maintains strong base projections, a significant -15% platoon penalty against Gray renders him unable to clear our 40.0 efficiency floor. Elsewhere, **Victor Scott II** (43.78) remains in the lineup despite a -8% penalty for his #9 hole, as his elite speed profile remains non-negotiable for our category strategy. Meanwhile, we continue to monitor the status of **Kazuma Okamoto**, currently slotted at #7 pending final confirmation; his score of 43.41 is anchored by his ability to handle Detmers, though we remain cautious of the -19% SP skill impact against a tough lefty. **Christian Yelich** remains sidelined, and we await better matchup conditions for the remainder of our bench, including **Lars Nootbaar**, **Zac Veen**, and **Josh Smith**.",
